📘 LLD Notes — Inheritance vs Composition
(Single Example: OrderService)

1️⃣ Problem Statement (Real-World)

We are building an Order Service.

Business requirements evolve over time:
    1. Order type: ONLINE, OFFLINE
    2. Payment method: CARD, UPI, WALLET
    3. Delivery type: HOME_DELIVERY, PICKUP

Goal:
    Clean design
    Easy to extend
    Minimal code changes

2️⃣ Naive Implementation — if-else Chain (Initial Approach)

class OrderService {

    public void processOrder(String orderType,
                             String paymentType,
                             String deliveryType) {

        if ("ONLINE".equals(orderType)) {

            if ("CARD".equals(paymentType)) {
                System.out.println("Online order paid via Card");
            } else if ("UPI".equals(paymentType)) {
                System.out.println("Online order paid via UPI");
            } else if ("WALLET".equals(paymentType)) {
                System.out.println("Online order paid via Wallet");
            }

            if ("HOME".equals(deliveryType)) {
                System.out.println("Home delivery");
            } else if ("PICKUP".equals(deliveryType)) {
                System.out.println("Store pickup");
            }

        } else if ("OFFLINE".equals(orderType)) {

            if ("CASH".equals(paymentType)) {
                System.out.println("Offline order paid via Cash");
            }

            System.out.println("Store pickup");
        }
    }
}

❌ Problems with if-else

    1. Violates Single Responsibility Principle
    2. Violates Open-Closed Principle
    3. Every new requirement → modify this class
    4. Hard to test
    5. Becomes a God class
👉 Senior engineers avoid this

3️⃣ First Refactor — Use Inheritance to Remove if-else

Base Class

abstract class OrderService {
    public abstract void processOrder();
}

Order Type Split

class OnlineOrderService extends OrderService {
    @Override
    public void processOrder() {
        System.out.println("Processing online order");
    }
}

class OfflineOrderService extends OrderService {
    @Override
    public void processOrder() {
        System.out.println("Processing offline order");
    }
}


✔ Order type if-else removed
✔ Looks clean initially

4️⃣ New Requirement — Payment Method
Why we create new subclasses?

If we add if-else inside OnlineOrderService, we go back to step 2 ❌
So we extend behavior using inheritance.

class OnlineCardOrderService extends OnlineOrderService {
    @Override
    public void processOrder() {
        System.out.println("Online order with Card payment");
    }
}

class OnlineUpiOrderService extends OnlineOrderService {
    @Override
    public void processOrder() {
        System.out.println("Online order with UPI payment");
    }
}
    

✔ No conditionals
✔ Polymorphism used properly

5️⃣ Next Requirement — Delivery Type

Now business says:
    “Online card orders can be Home Delivery or Pickup”

Where do we put this logic?
    Not in OnlineOrderService
    Not in OnlineCardOrderService (would need if-else again)

So we create more subclasses 👇

class OnlineCardHomeDeliveryOrderService
        extends OnlineCardOrderService {

    @Override
    public void processOrder() {
        System.out.println("Online Card Order with Home Delivery");
    }
}

class OnlineCardPickupOrderService
        extends OnlineCardOrderService {

    @Override
    public void processOrder() {
        System.out.println("Online Card Order with Store Pickup");
    }
}

6️⃣ Class Explosion Explained Clearly 💥

Each new independent requirement multiplies classes.

Dimensions:
Dimension	Count
Order Type	2
Payment	    3
Delivery	2
Total classes:
2 × 3 × 2 = 12 classes


Example names:

OnlineCardHomeDeliveryOrderService
OnlineCardPickupOrderService
OnlineUpiHomeDeliveryOrderService
OnlineWalletPickupOrderService
...


❌ Too many classes
❌ Hard to maintain
❌ Factory creation becomes nightmare

7️⃣ Where EXACTLY Change Happens (Important)

Add a new payment: CRYPTO

Required changes:
    New subclasses for ONLINE
    New subclasses for each delivery type
    Update factory logic

class OnlineCryptoHomeDeliveryOrderService extends OnlineOrderService {}
class OnlineCryptoPickupOrderService extends OnlineOrderService {}

🔥 Small feature → many new classes

8️⃣ Root Cause (Key Insight)

Inheritance tries to model multiple independent dimensions in a single hierarchy.

But:
    Payment
    Delivery
    Order type

are orthogonal concerns, not parent-child relationships.

9️⃣ Final Solution — Composition (Correct LLD)

Separate Responsibilities

interface Payment {
    void pay();
}

class CardPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Paid via Card");
    }
}

class UpiPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Paid via UPI");
    }
}

interface Delivery {
    void deliver();
}

class HomeDelivery implements Delivery {
    public void deliver() {
        System.out.println("Home delivery");
    }
}

class PickupDelivery implements Delivery {
    public void deliver() {
        System.out.println("Store pickup");
    }
}

OrderService Using Composition

class OrderService {

    private final Payment payment;
    private final Delivery delivery;

    public OrderService(Payment payment, Delivery delivery) {
        this.payment = payment;
        this.delivery = delivery;
    }

    public void processOrder() {
        payment.pay();
        delivery.deliver();
        System.out.println("Order processed");
    }
}

Usage (No Explosion)
OrderService order = new OrderService(new CardPayment(), new HomeDelivery());
order.processOrder();

🔟 Why Composition Wins
Aspect	Inheritance	Composition
if-else	❌	❌
Class explosion	❌	✅
OCP	❌	✅
SRP	❌	✅
Runtime flexibility	❌	✅
1️⃣1️⃣ Final Interview Summary (Memorize)

“Using inheritance to avoid if-else leads to class explosion when multiple independent dimensions exist. Composition solves this by separating concerns and assembling behavior at runtime.”